<Layout title="Third-Party Reproduction">
	<section class="page-header">
		<div class="container">
			<h1>Third-Party Reproduction</h1>
			<p>Building families with donor eggs, donor sperm, donor embryos, and gestational carriers.</p>
		</div>
	</section>

	<section class="content-container">
		<h2>Overview</h2>
		<p>Third-party reproduction involves using eggs, sperm, embryos, or a uterus from someone other than the intended parents. These options help individuals and couples who cannot conceive with their own gametes or carry a pregnancy.</p>

		<h2>Donor Sperm</h2>
		<div class="card">
			<h3>What It Is</h3>
			<p>Sperm from a donor used for insemination (IUI) or IVF.</p>

			<h3>Who Uses Donor Sperm</h3>
			<ul>
				<li>Single women</li>
				<li>Same-sex female couples</li>
				<li>Couples with severe male factor infertility</li>
				<li>Men with genetic conditions they don't want to pass on</li>
				<li>Azoospermia (no sperm in ejaculate) when surgical retrieval fails</li>
			</ul>

			<h3>Types of Donors</h3>
			<ul>
				<li><strong>Anonymous donors:</strong> Identity not disclosed; limited contact information</li>
				<li><strong>Open-ID donors:</strong> Identity available to child at age 18</li>
				<li><strong>Known donors:</strong> Friend or family member</li>
			</ul>

			<h3>Process</h3>
			<ol>
				<li>Select a sperm bank (California Cryobank, Seattle Sperm Bank, Fairfax, etc.)</li>
				<li>Review donor profiles (physical traits, education, health history)</li>
				<li>Purchase vials (ICI or IUI-ready)</li>
				<li>Ship to your clinic</li>
				<li>Use with IUI or IVF</li>
			</ol>

			<h3>Costs</h3>
			<table>
				<tbody>
					<tr>
						<td>Donor sperm vial</td>
						<td>$500-$1,200</td>
					</tr>
					<tr>
						<td>Extended profile/photos</td>
						<td>$50-$200</td>
					</tr>
					<tr>
						<td>Shipping</td>
						<td>$200-$400</td>
					</tr>
					<tr>
						<td>Storage at clinic</td>
						<td>$200-$500/year</td>
					</tr>
				</tbody>
			</table>
		</div>

		<h2>Donor Eggs</h2>
		<div class="card">
			<h3>What It Is</h3>
			<p>Eggs from a donor, fertilized with partner or donor sperm, with resulting embryo transferred to the recipient.</p>

			<h3>Who Uses Donor Eggs</h3>
			<ul>
				<li>Women with diminished ovarian reserve or premature ovarian insufficiency</li>
				<li>Repeated IVF failure with own eggs</li>
				<li>Advanced maternal age (typically &gt;42)</li>
				<li>Genetic conditions</li>
				<li>Women without ovaries (surgical removal, cancer)</li>
				<li>Same-sex male couples (with gestational carrier)</li>
			</ul>

			<h3>Types of Donor Egg Arrangements</h3>
			<ul>
				<li><strong>Fresh donor cycle:</strong> Synchronize with a donor for fresh eggs</li>
				<li><strong>Frozen donor eggs:</strong> Purchase from an egg bank</li>
				<li><strong>Known donor:</strong> Sister, friend, or other known person</li>
			</ul>

			<h3>Fresh vs. Frozen Eggs</h3>
			<table>
				<thead>
					<tr>
						<th>Factor</th>
						<th>Fresh</th>
						<th>Frozen</th>
					</tr>
				</thead>
				<tbody>
					<tr>
						<td>Cost</td>
						<td>$25,000-$45,000</td>
						<td>$15,000-$25,000</td>
					</tr>
					<tr>
						<td>Wait time</td>
						<td>2-6 months</td>
						<td>Immediate</td>
					</tr>
					<tr>
						<td>Eggs received</td>
						<td>All eggs from cycle (often 15-25)</td>
						<td>Set number (usually 6-8)</td>
					</tr>
					<tr>
						<td>Success rates</td>
						<td>55-65%</td>
						<td>45-55%</td>
					</tr>
				</tbody>
			</table>

			<h3>Cost Breakdown (Fresh Cycle)</h3>
			<table>
				<tbody>
					<tr>
						<td>Agency fee</td>
						<td>$5,000-$8,000</td>
					</tr>
					<tr>
						<td>Donor compensation</td>
						<td>$6,000-$15,000</td>
					</tr>
					<tr>
						<td>Donor screening/testing</td>
						<td>$3,000-$5,000</td>
					</tr>
					<tr>
						<td>Donor medications</td>
						<td>$3,000-$6,000</td>
					</tr>
					<tr>
						<td>Legal fees</td>
						<td>$1,500-$3,000</td>
					</tr>
					<tr>
						<td>IVF cycle (retrieval + transfer)</td>
						<td>$10,000-$15,000</td>
					</tr>
					<tr>
						<td><strong>Total</strong></td>
						<td><strong>$28,000-$52,000</strong></td>
					</tr>
				</tbody>
			</table>

			<h3>Success Rates</h3>
			<p>Donor egg IVF has high success rates because eggs come from young, healthy donors:</p>
			<ul>
				<li>50-65% live birth rate per transfer</li>
				<li>Success rates do NOT depend on recipient's age</li>
				<li>Cumulative success over multiple transfers: 80-90%</li>
			</ul>
		</div>

		<h2>Donor Embryos</h2>
		<div class="card">
			<h3>What It Is</h3>
			<p>Embryos donated by other couples who completed their families through IVF.</p>

			<h3>Who Uses Donor Embryos</h3>
			<ul>
				<li>Couples needing both donor egg and donor sperm</li>
				<li>Those seeking more affordable option than donor egg IVF</li>
				<li>Couples comfortable with embryo "adoption"</li>
			</ul>

			<h3>Process</h3>
			<ol>
				<li>Apply through embryo donation program or agency</li>
				<li>Match with donating family (often anonymous)</li>
				<li>Complete legal contracts</li>
				<li>Prepare uterus for transfer</li>
				<li>Frozen embryo transfer</li>
			</ol>

			<h3>Costs</h3>
			<table>
				<tbody>
					<tr>
						<td>Program/matching fee</td>
						<td>$3,000-$8,000</td>
					</tr>
					<tr>
						<td>Legal fees</td>
						<td>$1,000-$2,500</td>
					</tr>
					<tr>
						<td>Embryo transfer</td>
						<td>$3,000-$5,000</td>
					</tr>
					<tr>
						<td><strong>Total</strong></td>
						<td><strong>$7,000-$15,000</strong></td>
					</tr>
				</tbody>
			</table>

			<h3>Success Rates</h3>
			<p>30-50% per transfer (varies based on embryo quality and donor age at creation)</p>
		</div>

		<h2>Gestational Surrogacy</h2>
		<div class="card">
			<h3>What It Is</h3>
			<p>A gestational carrier (GC) carries a pregnancy for intended parents. The embryo is created through IVF using eggs and sperm from intended parents and/or donors - the carrier has no genetic connection to the baby.</p>

			<h3>Who Uses Gestational Surrogacy</h3>
			<ul>
				<li>Women without a uterus or with uterine problems</li>
				<li>Women with medical conditions making pregnancy dangerous</li>
				<li>Same-sex male couples</li>
				<li>Single men</li>
				<li>Repeated implantation failure or pregnancy loss</li>
			</ul>

			<h3>Types of Surrogacy</h3>
			<ul>
				<li><strong>Gestational surrogacy:</strong> GC has no genetic connection to baby (most common)</li>
				<li><strong>Traditional surrogacy:</strong> GC uses her own eggs (rare, more complex legally)</li>
			</ul>

			<h3>Process</h3>
			<ol>
				<li>Work with a surrogacy agency or find independent GC</li>
				<li>Extensive screening of potential carrier</li>
				<li>Legal contracts (required)</li>
				<li>IVF cycle: create embryos with intended parents' or donor gametes</li>
				<li>Transfer embryo(s) to gestational carrier</li>
				<li>Pregnancy and birth</li>
				<li>Legal process for parental rights</li>
			</ol>

			<h3>Costs</h3>
			<table>
				<tbody>
					<tr>
						<td>Agency fee</td>
						<td>$15,000-$30,000</td>
					</tr>
					<tr>
						<td>GC compensation</td>
						<td>$30,000-$60,000</td>
					</tr>
					<tr>
						<td>GC medical/psychological screening</td>
						<td>$3,000-$6,000</td>
					</tr>
					<tr>
						<td>Legal fees (both parties)</td>
						<td>$10,000-$20,000</td>
					</tr>
					<tr>
						<td>IVF + embryo transfer</td>
						<td>$15,000-$25,000</td>
					</tr>
					<tr>
						<td>GC health insurance or premiums</td>
						<td>$15,000-$35,000</td>
					</tr>
					<tr>
						<td>GC expenses (maternity clothes, travel, etc.)</td>
						<td>$5,000-$15,000</td>
					</tr>
					<tr>
						<td>Escrow management</td>
						<td>$1,000-$3,000</td>
					</tr>
					<tr>
						<td><strong>Total</strong></td>
						<td><strong>$100,000-$200,000</strong></td>
					</tr>
				</tbody>
			</table>

			<div class="warning-box">
				<strong>Legal Considerations:</strong> Surrogacy laws vary significantly by state. Some states are very surrogacy-friendly (California, Nevada, Connecticut); others have restrictions or bans. Work with a reproductive attorney experienced in your state's laws.
			</div>
		</div>

		<h2>Emotional and Ethical Considerations</h2>
		<ul>
			<li>Consider counseling before and during the process</li>
			<li>Think about disclosure: will you tell your child about their origins?</li>
			<li>Consider future contact with donors or carriers</li>
			<li>Research shows children conceived with donors do well when raised in supportive families</li>
		</ul>

		<div class="info-box">
			<strong>Disclosure:</strong> Child development experts generally recommend age-appropriate disclosure to children about their donor conception. Resources like the Donor Sibling Registry can help families connect.
		</div>

